{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012zZpPZJkj5wiBoiDW74wW5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of v1. Let me design and implement v2. Here's my plan:\n\n## V2 Design\n\n### Key improvements over v1:\n1. **Git worktree isolation** - each task gets its own worktree\n2. **Claude Code + Codex dual agent support** - `--agent claude|codex`\n3. **Steering support** - for Claude Code (interactive mode), Codex (stdin)\n4. **Auto retry with improved prompt** - up to 3 retries\n5. **Definition of Done** - custom check scripts\n6. **Better monitoring** - reads JSON registry + tmux status + gh cli\n\n\n7. **Cleaner code** - no patch accumulation\n\nI'll structure this with separate scripts for spawning tasks, checking status, retrieving results, steering agents mid-execution, killing tasks, and retrying with refined prompts. The registry will track active tasks in JSON format with their IDs, assigned agents, tmux sessions, and other metadata...\n\nDefining agent modes...\n\nI'm realizing the steering capability depends on whether we run Claude interactively or in print mode—interactive mode allows for steering via stdin but loses the stream-json output, while print mode gives us structured output but no interactivity. I should support both approaches with a `--steerable` flag to let users choose between fire-and-forget tasks with streaming JSON or interactive steerable tasks. Actually, the v1 approach of using `claude -p --output-format stream-json` already works well, so let me stick with that as the foundation. for logging. The \"steer\" issue in v1 was that it used `claude -p` which is non-interactive, so tmux send-keys wouldn't work.\n\nFor v2, I'm weighing the tradeoffs: running in stream-json mode gives me better logging but loses interactivity, while interactive mode allows steering but complicates logging. The key insight is that `claude -p` streams output without waiting for input, so terminal commands can't interrupt it, whereas interactive mode actually reads from stdin. I think the best path forward is launching in interactive mode and piping the initial prompt through stdin, which lets steering work via tmux send-keys while using tmux pipe-pane for output capture—though I'm not sure if that solves the real-time logging issues from v1. I'm settling on a simpler approach for v2: all tasks will use stream-json for consistent logging and progress tracking, while steering happens through tmux send-keys to interrupt and send new prompts. I need to check how Codex CLI behaves since it's a different binary, then design a clean spawn.sh script that handles both agent types with options for git worktree isolation and branch configuration.\n\nSetting up worktree support... I'm setting up the directory structure for the project under `~/.openclaw/workspace/memory/clawclau2/` with all the main scripts, and I'll create a shared library file to handle common operations like registry management, log file paths, and task updates to keep the bash code clean and avoid duplication across scripts.\n\nNow I'm thinking through Codex support—the CLI uses `codex` with flags like `--approval-mode full-auto` for automatic execution, but it doesn't support stream-json output formatting like Claude Code does, so I'll pipe the output directly to the log file instead.\n\nFor the architecture, I need to handle two different log formats: stream-json for Claude and plain text for Codex, which means both `result.sh` and the progress reporter need to account for this difference.\n\nI'm also considering a steering strategy—Claude has print mode for clean logging but limited interactivity, while both Claude and Codex support interactive mode via tmux for steering. So I'll add a `--steerable` flag that launches the agent interactively when needed, otherwise defaulting to the cleaner print/auto mode with stream-json logging.\n\nNow I'm working through how to actually send the initial prompt to Claude in steerable mode—using a heredoc through tmux works, but I need to make sure stdin stays available for steering afterward, or I could explore using `claude --resume` to handle the steering workflow differently.\n\nThe cleanest solution is launching Claude interactively without any prompt flags, then typing the initial prompt as the first input, which keeps the session open for subsequent steering commands. I'm setting this up by spawning a tmux session running Claude, waiting briefly, then sending the prompt text followed by Enter. For logging, I can pipe the session output to a file, though there might be some limitations with how much context gets captured that way.\n\nThe real distinction is between print mode, which streams JSON output without steering capability, and interactive mode, which gives us a proper terminal where we can send additional input and interrupt if needed. Now I'm thinking through how git worktree fits into this architecture...\n\nSetting up worktree support... Writing the shell scripts... Looking at the remaining scripts, `check.sh` reads the registry and tmux state to show task status without polling, while `result.sh` extracts the final output from logs based on agent type. The `steer.sh`, `kill.sh`, and `retry.sh` scripts handle steering messages to running tasks, terminating them with optional cleanup, and creating improved retry tasks respectively.\n\nBefore implementing the scripts, I should write a comprehensive DESIGN.md that covers the architecture, registry schema, agent selection logic, worktree lifecycle, monitoring approach, and the overall retry flow. Then I'll tackle the actual script implementations, starting with understanding the specific CLI interfaces for each agent type like Codex.\n\nFor parsing the stream-json logs from Claude Code, I'm building a jq filter that prioritizes the result event first, falls back to the last assistant message if needed, and can reconstruct text from delta fragments as a final option.\n\nNow I'm ready to write everything out with clean, production-ready code that keeps each script self-contained while sourcing a shared library, focusing on correctness and clarity over unnecessary complexity.\n\nFor the interactive steerable mode in spawn.sh, I need to handle how Claude Code actually works—starting it in tmux with the initial prompt, then using tmux pipe-pane to capture output while keeping the session open for follow-up steering commands. The PTY handling should work correctly for logging even in interactive mode.\n\nFor logging, steerable mode will capture raw terminal output with ANSI codes rather than clean JSON, which result.sh will need to parse by stripping the escape sequences. The non-steerable default mode will stick with the stream-json format from v1 for cleaner logging.\n\nFor Codex in v2, I'll use full-auto approval mode with plain text logging via tee, since Codex operates differently than Claude Code despite both being interactive tools.\n\nNow I'm realizing steer.sh needs to handle the case where Claude is running in print mode without stdin—I can either reject the steering request or kill and respawn the process with the steering message appended to the prompt. The second approach is actually more useful as a form of kill-and-retry with clarification, so I'll implement that logic to check the task mode and either send keys to the tmux session or restart with the amended prompt.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. I'll keep steer.sh straightforward: for steerable mode it sends keys via tmux, and for print mode it tells the user to use retry.sh or kill.sh instead.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out all the scripts. I'll keep the code reasonably concise without excessive comments, and I'm planning to create DESIGN.md for the architecture, then lib.sh for shared utilities, spawn.sh as the main entry point, check.sh for status checking, result.sh for extracting results, steer.sh for mid-task steering, and kill.sh for termination.\n\nWriting spawn.sh now... Finishing the argument parsing and then validating the required inputs—checking that the agent is either claude or codex, ensuring the task ID follows the right format, and setting up the working directory with a fallback to the current directory.\n\nNow I'm checking that all the necessary command-line tools are available, initializing the logging and prompt directories, and setting up the tmux session name and file paths I'll need for this task.\n\nChecking if a tmux session already exists for this task ID, then setting up a git worktree if requested—determining the repository root, branch name, and worktree path before creating it.\n\nNow I'm writing a wrapper script that will launch Claude in the agent working directory, with different configurations depending on whether steerable mode is enabled. Setting up the tmux session and piping output...\n\nNow I'm verifying the session started successfully and handling any startup errors, then registering the task with its configuration details like the agent type, session name, prompt, and working directories.\n\nSetting up a background process that monitors the tmux session and will handle cleanup once it terminates...\n\nNow I'm checking if the done-check script exists and is executable, running it to validate the task completion, then updating the registry with the final status and timestamp before triggering a system refresh.\n\nThen I'm sending a notification event with the task result, spawning it in the background, and if progress reporting is enabled, starting that as a separate background process too. Finally, I'm outputting a summary of what was spawned—the task ID, agent details, session info, working directory, and timeout settings.\n\nNow I need to actually write out these files, being careful about the implementation details. There's a subtle issue with how I'm handling the prompt in the wrapper for non-steerable mode—I need to think through whether variable substitution should happen at spawn time or at execution time. With an unquoted heredoc delimiter, substitution happens when the heredoc is written. With a quoted delimiter, it doesn't. The v1 approach used a quoted delimiter and evaluated the prompt at wrapper execution time, which gives more flexibility.\n\nFor v2, I'll simplify by baking the paths directly into the wrapper at write time using an unquoted heredoc, which is cleaner and avoids the extra indirection.\n\nActually, I need to be careful here—an unquoted heredoc evaluates variables at write time, so `$(cat \"$PROMPT_FILE\")` would embed the prompt content immediately rather than reading it at runtime. I should keep the variable references in the wrapper so they're evaluated when the script actually runs. Writing the wrapper script... Writing wrapper scripts... I'm realizing there's a fundamental issue with how to pass the initial prompt in steerable mode—`tmux send-keys` struggles with multi-line text and special characters, and piping from a file breaks the interactive TTY that Claude needs for subsequent input. The real solution is to launch Claude with a proper PTY and then send keystrokes to it, but that requires a different approach than what I've outlined so far. I'm realizing `tmux paste-buffer` with the `-p` flag might not work as expected for stdin—let me reconsider whether this actually sends data to the process's stdin or just pastes it as typed input.\n\nLooking back at the v1 steering implementation, it just uses `tmux send-keys` for everything, so maybe I should stick with that simpler approach and accept that special characters might need escaping for follow-up steers, or document that limitation for users.\n\nNow I'm settling on my implementation strategy: default to pipe mode for clean logging, use interactive mode with tmux steering when the user requests it, and for non-interactive corrections just kill and respawn with the updated prompt.\n\nI'm debating whether worktrees should be automatic or opt-in—the reference suggests always using them for isolation, but since not every project is a git repo, I'll make it an optional flag. For codex, I'll stick with the `--approval-mode full-auto` flag to skip manual approvals and keep things moving.\n\nWriting the bash implementation now...\n\nBuilding the registry functions with jq... Now I'm laying out all the shell scripts I need to create for this task management system—a design document, shared library functions, and individual scripts for spawning tasks, checking status, extracting results, steering mid-execution, terminating, retrying with better prompts, and documentation. Let me start writing them all out.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2178,"cache_read_input_tokens":28721,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2178},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dec3f60-2165-4422-8434-2be6f8f9065a","uuid":"9dc7e887-50b5-47bf-80ba-79287bd1c138"}
