{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016Beg98ZdW5QXR8qBu4pnk1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the function works when tested from that directory. The issue is that in the earlier test, the log file was `/tmp/test-result.json` but I wrote the content correctly.\n\nWait - the earlier test was a completely separate CC_HOME setup. Let me look more carefully...\n\nIn the earlier test, I wrote the fake log to `/tmp/test-result.json` and registered the task with `\"log\": \"/tmp/test-result.json\"`.\n\nThen in `result.sh`:\n```bash\nLOG_FILE=$(cc_task_get \"$TASK_ID\" \"log\")\n```\n\nThis should return `/tmp/test-result.json`.\n\n\nThen it calls the extraction function on that log file. But I think I see the issue now - I cleaned up the test file with `rm /tmp/test-result.json` at the end of the test, so when result.sh tried to read it later, the file was already gone.\n\nLet me trace through the test sequence more carefully. The test registers a task pointing to `/tmp/test-result.json`, writes fake log data there, runs check.sh, runs result.sh, then cleans up - but both check and result should have executed before that cleanup happened. \n\nLooking back at the test code, I notice `CC_HOME` is set using the PID at assignment time, not at test execution time. The log file itself is written to `/tmp/test-result.json` outside of CC_HOME, which should be fine. I think the real issue might be with the test data I created - let me check what I actually wrote to that stream.json file to see if it's in the right format. The issue is becoming clearer—both `check.sh` and `result.sh` are showing empty results, but the `cc_extract_text` function works fine when I test it directly with the same JSON format. I'm realizing the problem might be in how the log path is being passed or resolved. Let me trace through what's happening: `check.sh` extracts the log path from the task JSON using `jq`, then passes it to `cc_extract_text`, but something in that chain isn't working as expected. and not deleted). The content was the same. So the function does work. Let me trace through what's actually happening by running the test again to see where it fails. I'm wondering if the issue is that `check.sh` can't find `lib.sh` when it sources it with a relative path, even though the `SCRIPT_DIR` logic should handle that correctly. Let me verify the path resolution is working as expected.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":638,"cache_read_input_tokens":63207,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":638},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dec3f60-2165-4422-8434-2be6f8f9065a","uuid":"ad3bc42e-1653-4650-9a58-2099b086a311"}
