{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UNM5jwhjNqGe3LFhaDZ4K5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found it! The subshell test fails. When `bash -c 'source lib.sh; cc_extract_text ...'` is run, it returns empty string. This is because in the `cc_extract_text` function, there's a call to `jq -rs '...'`. The jq multiline string is the problem. Let me check if it's because the heredoc inside a function in bash -c has issues.\n\nActually, the jq filter in lib.sh uses single quotes in the jq filter string. When the entire function body is sourced in bash -c, maybe there's a quoting issue?\n\nActually wait - when `bash -c` creates a new shell, it doesn't inherit functions from the parent shell (unlike sourcing). \n\nThe `source lib.sh` should re-define all functions, but I need to make sure the path is absolute since the subshell might not have the right working directory. I used `/Users/yjj/.openclaw/workspace/memory/clawclau2/lib.sh` in the test, so that should be fine. Let me test the jq command directly in a subshell to isolate the issue.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":891,"cache_read_input_tokens":67759,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":891},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dec3f60-2165-4422-8434-2be6f8f9065a","uuid":"6ef21899-1039-44fe-ab5a-398d4bd2eb60"}
