{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017pexkFjvQ7LmdtaD7Um5Cw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found it! macOS ships with bash 3.2, and `${text: -500}` with a larger offset than the string length returns EMPTY in bash 3.2! This is the bug.\n\nIn bash 4+, `${text: -500}` where 500 > length returns the full string. In bash 3.2, it returns empty when the offset exceeds the string length.\n\nThe fix is to either:\n1. Use `/usr/bin/env bash` which still uses bash 3.2 on macOS\n2. Use a different approach to get the \"last N chars\" that works in bash 3.2\n\n\n3. Check the string length first and only apply the slice if the text is actually longer than the max character limit\n\nI'm testing a few approaches to handle this in bash 3.2 — checking the length upfront and conditionally slicing, or using command-line tools like `tail -c` to extract the last N characters, though I need to account for the newline that gets added.\n\nThe cleanest solution is to check the text length first: if it's within the limit, return it as-is, otherwise grab the last N characters using the substring syntax. This avoids any edge cases where the offset might exceed the string length.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":846,"cache_read_input_tokens":76633,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":846},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dec3f60-2165-4422-8434-2be6f8f9065a","uuid":"68eddf3a-11b9-4480-a774-a20c03d08ce4"}
